Earth and Environmental Sciences, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; Lo, K., SGT Incorporated, New York, NY 10025, United States; Menon, S., Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Novakov, T., Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Perlwitz, J., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States, Columbia Earth Institute, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; Russell, G., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States; Schmidt, G.A., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States, Columbia Earth Institute, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; Tausnev, N., SGT Incorporated, New York, NY 10025, United States","Our climate model, driven mainly by increasing human-made greenhouse gases and aerosols, among other forcings, calculates that Earth is now absorbing 0.85 ± 0.15 watts per square meter more energy from the Sun than it is emitting to space. This imbalance is confirmed by precise measurements of increasing ocean heat content over the past 10 years. Implications include (i) the expectation of additional global warming of about 0.6°C without further change of atmospheric composition; (ii) the confirmation of the climate system's lag in responding to forcings, implying the need for anticipatory actions to avoid any specified level of climate change; and (iii) the likelihood of acceleration of ice sheet disintegration and sea level rise.",,"Aerosols; Atmospheric composition; Earth atmosphere; Energy absorption; Enthalpy; Greenhouse effect; Sea level; Solar energy; Climate systems; Energy imbalance; Greenhouse gases; Ice sheets; Climate change; climate change; energy balance; accuracy; aerosol; article; climate change; energy absorption; energy balance; global climate; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; heat; priority journal; sea; sea ice; sea level",,,,,,"Hans